    <section>
        <h2>Touchdown in Gambia</h2>
        <p>After landing, a shuttle bus will ferry you to the main terminal building. It's worth noting that the climate
            inside the airport is generally warm. Therefore, storing your jackets in your carry-on luggage is advisable
            before disembarking. Also, keep your passport, along with all relevant documents, and a pen at hand for easy
            access.</p>
    </section>
    <section>
        <h2>Airport Development Fee</h2>
        <p>The Banjul International Airport levies a development fee of €20/$20/£20 or GMD1000 per person (excluding
            infants). This fee needs to be paid at the Airport Security Tax collection desk.</p>
    </section>
    <section>
        <h2>Immigration Checkpoint</h2>
        <p>Next, you'll be directed to the immigration control section where your passport (with visa if applicable)
            will be checked. You'll be asked to provide your biometrics and pose for a photograph.</p>
    </section>
    <section>
        <h2>Baggage Claim</h2>
        <p>Moving ahead, you'll arrive at the luggage carousel area. Be prepared for a bit of a wait here. It's
            advisable to carry water or other drinks in your hand luggage as the temperature may sometimes be
            uncomfortable. Trolleys are provided free of charge; however, if you decide to use a porter's services, be
            ready to tip them around £1/€1.50/$2.</p>
    </section>
    <section>
        <h2>Luggage Security Check</h2>
        <p>After your luggage arrives, proceed to the baggage security queue. Here, your luggage will be scanned by an
            X-ray machine. From this point, you may leave the main building complex. Remember to keep your luggage
            number handy as it may be required at the exit area.</p>
    </section>
